rComments: He gave excellent lectures that made even complex metaphysical ideas quite approachable. We only had a midterm and a final exam but the questions were pretty easy to answer if you've reviewed the course content and study questions thoroughly.

A fantastic and thorough lecturer. David Hyder is a great philosophy professor and I was extremely lucky to have him teach me modern philosophy. This class is not easy, and you need to do pretty much all the readings and the lectures to understand. However, if you put in the effort, you will get the grade. There were only two exams, but both fair.
teacherRatingTags: ['Graded by few things', 'Caring', 'Get ready to read']

rComments: Have had him for two COMPULSORY courses for my major, and he has been incredible. You can immediately tell he KNOWS what he's talking about, care about it and cares that his students understand. He explains extremely harsh metaphysical topics with ease and which are actually easy to really understand. Listen to lectures and you'll be fine!!!!

Overall I really enjoyed being in his class! He made the content fairly interesting and it's clear that he genuinely cares about wanting his students to succeed. He's also not a super tough grader, he just wants to make sure you understand the material. Just take notes during his lectures and you'll definitely do well.

Modern Philosophy. Blown away by the intelligence of Dr. Hyder and his ability to explain increasingly deep topics. Had my mind blown by the end of almost every lecture! Concise in explanations of particular philosophers' view points and their interactions with each other. Really painted a picture.

This class is just a 35% midterm and 65% final, so if tests aren't for you, I'd skip it. The course content is certainly not what I expected (this is basically a metaphysics course) but Hyder makes it interesting enough.

David Hyder is a wonderfully passionate professor and condenses the very disparate topics philosophers have historically been interested in regarding metaphysics into an interesting narrative concerning the nature of change, time and space that allowed me to gain a deeper appreciation and understanding for all the thinkers he touched on.
Really kind and fair marker, wants to see the student succeed rather than stick to strict deadlines. Always available outside of class to explain material,

Dr. Hyder is a very sweet prof and clearly cares for students and gives you all the tools to succeed. If you dont try then your grades will suffer, but as long as you take good notes its an easy A. IMO the content was boring, but Hyder was charismatic. Take this if you enjoy phi and are able to follow along (its easy to get lost during lectures)

Honestly, I didn't totally enjoy the course material and found some of the concepts hard to grasp. But Professor Hyder is awesome. The way he speaks is very captivating and enjoyable. It is clear that he is very kind and passionate. He was always understanding when students were struggling.

Dr. Hyder is a great professor, he is very passionate about the subject. Personally, I do not like philosophy but he made it seem a little better. Overall, an okay course, I wouldn't take again though :/
teacherRatingTags: ['Graded by few things', 'Lecture heavy', 'Get ready to read']

rComments: An amazing prof who is passionate about what he teaches. Most times he seems to go off tangent while lecturing, so refer to either the textbook or ask the TA after class if you have questions. If you can answer the practice exam questions, you should be good to go. Midterms aren't too bad, just make sure to write your own notes during the class.

He is clearly passionate and knowledgeable about what he teaches. His actual lecturing is quite good, but sometimes the nature of the content and the speed at which he delivers it makes information hard to absorb immediately. Look over his lecture notes and you'll be fine, and don't be afraid to reach out after class.

Another great PHI prof. His lectures are a little hard to follow so pay attention. Doing the readings is unnecessary as his explanations are good (assuming you keep up). His powerpoints are very useful and always tries to do a review. Generally a midterm + final.  Extremely easy to get a hold of outside of class hours. Seek his help if needed.

J'ai suivis deux cours avec monsieur Hyder, dont PHI3782.  -pars facilement sur des tangentes -cours très denses dû à la quantité de matière qu'il veux enseigner  -répond RAPIDEMENT aux couriels -Est très aimable pour répondre au question à l'extérieur de ses heures de cours  -cet homme est une banque de connaissance !!!

Hyder is an extremely knowledgeable man and very passionate about his stuff. He answers emails promptly and cares about his students. The class matter is very interesting but can be a bit confusing at times. In terms of difficulty, I would definitely not consider this a first year course. Exams reflect class matter to 100% but are challenging!

His lectures aren't bad, but he does go off on tangents. His slides are atrocious. It's very difficult to grasp concepts from them. His tests are very simple, though he does like to combine two different topics as application questions. If you understand the concepts, then they're are super easy. His marking is easy, but his TA's was ridiculous.

Hyder is an incredibly unfocused professor who should be writing books, not teaching students. Lectures are basically him rambling on about random spin-off theories that are irrelevant and simply confuse from the core material at hand. His slides are atrotious and no less confusing than hearing him talk. AVOID AT ALL COSTS

I find him to be quite rude to his students, very degrading when they try and participate. Unless you are a fanstudent of philo it is very hard to understand him.   He's a nice person when not talking about philo, just not someone I want to attempt to learn from.  I fully expect the exam to be just as cryptic as the lectures.

This prof made the class material incredibly hard to understand. The only way I learned the material was from a philosophy tutor and reading the textbook. Good part is that his tests aren't too difficult and the textbook is very small and only $11

You can find all his slides online, exam questions are given out. so read on the course web. exam questions look terrifying,  many people quit after the midterm without knowing he is generous marker. I would say he is the best prof at ottawaU, passionate about subject, care about his students, most importantly he tries to understand students

This was an interesting and enjoyable class. Professor Hyder is an incredibly intelligent man with an abundance of knowledge. However, this can make class  difficult to follow sometimes depending on your familiarity with science. The readings were usually clear and informative. To do well, it helps to really understand the concepts he discusses.

Le cours était interressant, les lectures étaient assez difficile mais le prof explique très bien et adopte une approche très professionelle, contrairement aux commentaires des autres étudiants. Par contre, il faut etre très attentif(ve) en classe pour avoir de bonnes notes. Très sympa and  helpful. Highly recommended
I found Professor Hyder to be very passionate about the subject matter and genuinely concerned about the student's learning. All good students will find him insightful and engaging.

Don't recommend this prof. He assumes you know everything about philosophy, requires you to take time out of your schedule to meet his requirements and then uses a question (worth 30%) that you havent learnt. Beware of him.

Very intelligent prof; however, he does not convey the subject matter effectively.  The TA was far more helpful than the Prof (especially the Logic portion of the course). I would not recommend taking any course taught by this professor.

Professor Hyder is a very nice person but his lectures are long and confusing! His way of explaining the logic sequence was terrible. If it were not for the review sessions with the TA I would not have passed this course. If you want to pass your mandatory Philo class I suggest you take it with another prof.
He is very fair when it comes to midterms and exams. He lets you know exactly what to expect, there are no surprises. As long as you study you should be fine.

Hyder is the only thing getting me through this semester. There are so many challenged professors at the University of Ottawa... Hyder is NOT one of them. He is brilliant! The subject matter is very complex but if you take the time to review your notes and ponder the concepts discussed in class, it can be very interesting.

Hyder's detailed explanations and personal, no-BS style make him a great prof, at least for upper-year classes. His lectures are very interesting  provided you have any interest in the material to begin with. Asks tough questions, which keeps students attentive.

Really knows his stuff. Very boring lectures though it's very hard to pay attention. He posts all the lectures/things you need to know on V campus however. First quiz was unfair, second was easy/fair. learnt a lot though, he was okay overall didn't love him though. it's also all from the textbook
Not very kind, bordering on rude, easy tests if you read the textbook (which was very cheap). Speaks quite fast and makes you  zone out. Over all not a hard class, just not enjoyable.

Smart man who knows his stuff. Not a good prof at an introductory level. He expects his first years to know a lot of terminology which we don't. I assume he would be great for upper year courses. Very annoying mannerisms. I don't enjoy listening to or watching him lecture.

I LOVE this teacher. I just wish he was more available outside of class for questions and the like... However, his classes are fascinating, I learnt so much and it was only an introductory class. You have to study hard and listen up... but why else would we be in university? Just to daydream? I don't think so! :)
awesome

Third course with Prof. Hyder and it's great. I recently sent him an e-mail question about vocab and got a detailed answer with 24 hours that was very clear and helpful. Also flexible with deadlines IF you have a good reason. If you work hard, you'll be able to get a solid mark, and you'll actually learn a lot! Highly recommend him.

This professor might be handsome and intelligent but beyond the textbook you're pretty much on your own. It doesn't help that the textbook is only marginally less dry and cryptic as the actual classes.

Probably the worst person, let alone teacher i have ever met. He is rude to students and has no time for actually teaching. He expects students to know everything from the beginning. He insults students in front of the class and in emails. He should be kicked out of the university. He is definitely a person you want to avoid AT ALL COSTS!

Definitely my least enjoyable class of first year.. I can't say if it's the prof or the material. The material is definitely confusing to start off with, but the Hyder seems to present a lot of information, which makes it hard to know what is important.

The subject matter is itself very convoluted and difficult to teach. Hyder takes a long time to accomplish very little (we only got through half the material). You must go beyond the material in the text to complete your understanding. I've never worked so hard for an A. Avoid if you are not a deep thinker. One midterm 40%, one final paper 60%.

First I would like to say that he knows his stuff and isn't a total idiot.  That being said, he is however extremely lazy.  He will not teach you anything and expects you to teach yourself from the textbook.  You should just take an online course.  He doesn't come prepared to class and is often tardy.

Prof. Hyder is the worst prof I have had. He is confusing and incoherent. He goes off on random asides that have nothing to do with the material and it is hard to figure out when he picks the material back up. Stay away from this prof if you want to learn. I believe he has a lot of knowledge, but cannot communicate it. VERY poor educator.

I found it very hard to do well in this class. Hyder has his powerpoint presentations up on the internet which was helpful. the subject matter in this course was boring, i found it hard to do well, but i REALLY appreciated that he told people who were talking to shut up. i didnt mind hyder but i strongly disliked the course.

Hyder fails.  He treats a first year class like they're fourth years, like they should know what he's talking about without being told.  He shouldn't have been teaching this year.  He missed more classes than all my other professors combined, including a mid-term!
I enjoy his lecture style, some may have trouble following with his use of abstract advanced ideas, but learning generally is the point of school.
ya worste class ever. It will make you want to drop out of first year.

Worst prof I've ever had.  He is unclear and boring.  If consulted for help, he simply sends you away with little or no advice.  At best, he tells you to drop the course.  Take Great Philosophers and Critical Thinking instead of this one.
A mean little egotistical jerk. Avoid him at all costs.

Dont even think emailing him to ask him a question because he will send u two scentence reply saying you should ask it in class..if u dislike philosphy u will hate it from his class..he is so full of himself..

This course with him is very very boring. Half of the class falls asleep. I barely went to class because it made me tired and not able to listen to him. He has a very monotone voice which doesnt help at all, and if you email him a question, he doesnt give you an actual answer. I would not suggest taking this course with him!
He can sometimes be a little dry, he has a good sense of humour and he presents the material clearly. I'd happily take a more advanced course from him.
Stay away from this class if you can! He presents the subject matter, but doesn't actually *teach* it... So very, very dry. It doesn't have to be, though... See Dr. Forster...
Awesome.
Competent, but needs to work on his presentation. Seems rather self important.
To monotone. Boring to listen to...does not spark my interest at all. Good course though.

I have taken quite a few philosophy classes at the University of Ottawa and this one is by far the most boring and unclear.  The professor makes things far too complicated!  The subject matter is pretty basic... it just seems that he likes to hear the sound of his own voice!
Very boring class, but all the information is given to you clearly, and he readily answers questions. Tests are easy enough if you actually pay attention and do the work.

I dont know what everyone else has been saying, but Professor Hyder has been a great prof, and anyone who doesnt like the guy just because he wont accept a fake doctors note should seriously sit down and think about why you are here.

The prof makes things much more difficult than they need to be...esp PROOFS *ppl who've had his class will know what i mean*. Lectures are very unclear and some test questions are unfair... they are awkwardly worded and confusing. Very BORING class.
i have to disagree! he makes everything so much more complicated than it has to be...and drier than it has to be...definetly not a fun class
Incredibly intellectual guy. Sometimes it is hard to follow, but that’s just a result of his depth and knowledge.
The class material is pretty dry, and he's a little boring to listen to... but he can be funny, and he's a nice guy.  He's fair.
Clear and organised (though he's a little vain!)
